Biofilm-forming capacity was assessed using the maximum cell index recorded from xCELLigence. Biofilm formation was assessed over a 12-hour period using xCELLigence-derived cell index values. In addition to the maximum biofilm-forming capacity, we derived kinetic features for each sample, including the time to maximum biofilm formation and the total biofilm burden (area under the curve). 
A total of 36 biofilm samples were included in the analysis. The mean maximum biofilm index was 0.189 (SD = 0.081; median = 0.179). Biofilm samples reached peak accumulation at a mean of 6.54 hours (SD = 1.95; median = 6.51 hours), consistent with a growth trajectory that plateaus around the mid-point of the 12-hour observation window. 
Biofilm formation over time was first visualised using observed growth curves. A marked increase in biofilm formation was observed between approximately 4 and 7 hours, after which the curve plateaued. These findings suggest that the main period of biofilm accumulation occurred between 4 and 8 hours.
Area under the curve was used as a summary measure of total biofilm burden over time. This measure captures both the magnitude and duration of biofilm formation during the 12-hour observation period. Higher AUC values indicate that a sample formed more biofilm overall, either because it reached a higher cell index, maintained an elevated cell index for longer, or both. AUC reflects both the extent of biofilm formation and its persistence.
